{
  "doc_id": "47520",
  "text": "Autophagy is a housekeeping and nutrient recycling process in which cellular components, debris, and other macromolecules are delivered to or engulfed by lysosomes for degeneration [CITATION_1] . Impaired autophagy is central to the progression of PD [CITATION_2] . Deletion of genes essential for autophagy, such as ATG7, produces PD-like neurodegeneration in mice [CITATION_3] . Accumulation of ␣Syn is one of the pathological hallmarks of PD and may be both a cause and a consequence of impaired autophagy [CITATION_4] . ␣Syn is normally cleared by a combination of the ubiquitin-proteasome system (UPS), chaperonemediated autophagy (CMA), and macroautophagy [CITATION_5] . However, oligomerization of ␣Syn prevents clearance by UPS and CMA, increasing the necessity of macroautophagy-mediated clearance, which involves the formation of an autophagosome to sequester cytoplasmic constituents and transport them to lysosomes. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Yet, there is evidence that macroautophagy is also impaired in PD [CITATION_8] .",
